Multiple inheritance - Order of parent classes

1)	In Class definition:	
	class DiamondTrap : public ScavTrap, public FragTrap {};
	
	What does this order mean?
	The order in which parent classes are listed in the class definition (public ScavTrap, public FragTrap) 
	only affects the order in which they are inherited. 
	It does not dictate the order of initialization.

	How does the order of inheritance matter?
	Order of Inheritance: 
		The order determines which base class's member is chosen when there are ambiguities 
		due to multiple inheritance.
		
		If you called a common member attribute, without specifying ScavTrap or FragTrap,
		It will ScavTrap would be used, because it is listed first.

2) 	In Constructor Initialization list:
	DiamondTrap::DiamondTrap(void) : FragTrap(), ScavTrap()
	
	What does this order mean?
	The order in which base class constructors are called is determined by the order 
	in which they appear in the constructor's initialization list, 
	not the order in the class definition. 
	
	In other words, constructors of base classes are called in the order 
	they appear in the initialization list of the derived class's constructor.
